         <div class="block block-views" id="block-views-featured-stories-block-1">
          <div class="content">
           <div class="view view-featured-stories view-id-featured_stories view-display-id-block_1 view-dom-id-5915ade9d94913351f61b71c595ead13">
            <div class="view-content">
             <div class="views-row views-row-1 views-row-odd views-row-first views-row-last">
              <div class="views-field views-field-nothing">
               <span class="field-content">
                <div class="bean-left">
                 <img alt="The Three-body Problem by Cixin Liu book cover" height="400" src="https://eap.einaudi.cornell.edu/sites/eap/files/styles/front_large/public/three%20body%20problem%20audio%20book%20cover.jpg?itok=q8H9HPON" typeof="foaf:Image" width="800"/>
                </div>
                <div class="right">
                 <h2>
                  <a href="/story/march-18-sci-fi-author-ken-liu-give-talk-and-book-signing-cornell">
                   March 18 Sci-fi author Ken Liu to give talk and book signing at Cornell
                  </a>
                 </h2>
                 <p>
                  On March 18, Ken Liu, award winning science fiction author, and translator of such stellar works as Liu Cixin’s "Three-body Problem", speaks on, “Betrayal with Integrity: Conformance and Estrangement in Translating Chinese Science Fiction”. This one-hour lecture which discusses the origin of Chinese science fiction through the translation of Western works is part of the Cornell Contemporary China Initiative lecture series (
                  <a href="https://eap.einaudi.cornell.edu/ccci-lecture-series">
                   https://eap.einaudi.cornell.edu/ccci-lecture-series
                  </a>
                  ).
                 </p>
                 <p>
                  4:30 Klarman Hall KG70 Free and open to the public
                 </p>
                 <p>
                  A winner of the Nebula, Hugo, and World Fantasy awards, Ken Liu is the author of multiple books including but not limited to "The Dandelion Dynasty", a silkpunk epic fantasy series, "The Grace of Kings"(2015), and the Star Wars novel, "The Legends of Luke Skywalker" (2017). His short story, 'The Paper Menagerie' became the first work of fiction to win the Nebula, the Hugo and the World Fantasy Award. This event is sponsored by the East Asia Program and the Einaudi Center for International Studies.  It is generously co-sponsored by the Cornell Society of the Humanities and the Ithaca College Department of Writing.
                 </p>
                </div>
               </span>
              </div>
             </div>
            </div>
           </div>
          </div>
